PY  - 2011
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - The Sunshine Coast Shoreline Erosion Management Plan (SCSEMP) has been developed to set clear guidelines for the future protection and management of coastal erosion between Caloundra and Noosa Heads, including the Mooloolah and Maroochy River Entrances. The study area represents the second most popular coastal destination in South-East Queensland after the Gold Coast but has not been studied in the same detail. The SCSEMP was developed on two decisive aspects: a determination of the long-term coastal processes (being the net loss of sand) and a risk based analysis for management options. The need for and nature of options to deal with coastal erosion is dependent on the level of threat and associated consequences. There are sections of the study area where there is no immediate or long-term erosion threat to existing development, and areas where there is substantial development under more immediate threat. Management options for these areas vary accordingly. The SCSEMP, in broad terms, considered two basic approaches to dealing with erosion. The first is to retreat from the area prone to erosion and allow the natural erosion processes to occur. The second is to hold the line using soft and/or hard coastal engineering methods to protect public and private assets. This option requires a careful assessment of the impact to natural coastal processes. A risk continuum tool has been considered when developing the SCSEMP recommendations. The tool, originally developed for climate change adaptation studies, has been used to assist the planning and management of coastal assets within the study area. This approach identifies the acceptable risks, the unacceptable consequences and determines the timing of intervention based on pre-defined 'triggers for action'. A trigger-based approach, as opposed to a time-based approach, provides a framework to manage coastal erosion threats yet to be realised such as sea level rise.
