AB  - The National Institute for Coastal and Harbor Infrastructure (NICHI), working with the Metro NY-NJ storm surge working group (SSWG), is a collaborating team of economists, engineers, oceanographers, meteorologists, geologists, ecologists, architects, social scientists, policy makers, consultants, and private citizens. NICHI is serving as a clearinghouse for research and advocacy, exploring the premise that the future protection of metropolitan New York from catastrophic extreme weather events and climate change necessitates a regional approach that transcends geographical and political boundaries. Using recent scientific, engineering, and economic evaluations, NICHI advocates the construction of moveable marine-based storm surge barriers at two strategic locations: between Sandy Hook and Far Rockaway (to arrest ocean surges) and across the upper East River (to block surges from Long Island Sound). The navigation gates would normally be open to shipping traffic, but activated only when a significant storm surge threat is forecast. Such a system could have a useful working life of at least 100 years, when sea level may have risen by similar to 2 m; at that time, a planned retreat inland may be necessary. NICHI is working to develop a consensus among elected officials, agency personnel, advisory groups, policy makers, and stakeholders on risk reduction and mitigation measures; disseminate information on the risks of climate change and extreme storm events to the public and governmental officials. NICHI seeks to provide agencies such as the Army Corps of Engineers and supporting state and city agencies creative ideas and information necessary for the evaluation of risk reduction, cost/benefits, design, construction, and operational costs necessary to fully develop a long-term regional plan to protect Metropolitan New York as a world center of finance, business, transportation, communication, medicine, and the arts.
