AB  - The IPCC forth assessment reported that the global mean sea level will rise by up to 59cm due to the melting of snow and glaciers on the land and thermal expansion of sea water if no effort is made to reduce emissions of green house gas. In an extreme prediction lowland areas in Korea could be vulnerable to inundation by a sea level rise of 69cm, which is 10 cm above that of the global mean. The area would be inundated by up to 393.44km(2) for a 60 cm rise in sea level, with total damage of US\$ 26,046 million in the dry land areas only. The highest cost of the damage is expected to be observed in the most industrialized areas of Korea with the highest annual income, even though the inundation would be most serious in the Jeonnam area. While areas will be inundated depending on their morphological characteristics, the socio and economic factors are also critical determinants of the cost of damage. A damage cost assessment is the first step in constructing policies and measures for responding to the rising sea level. The present cost estimation could be a component for the basis of building an adaptation strategy.
