AB  - The strengthening of capacities for building resilience is a pending task in the coastal area of Ecuador. We work in resilience as a process to promote a culture of prevention and preparedness against natural hazards. One of the detected weaknesses in a coastal community, through a participatory diagnosis, has been the little concern to be prepared to face natural disasters, not having contingency plans nor warning measures. The academy can be an inclusive actor in this process, demonstrated in the development of the community intervention project ``Empowerment of community capacities to improve the resilience capacity to extreme events and threats of marine and anthropogenic origin with affectation in the coastal zone{''}, with the participation of teachers and students. This paper aims to describe the methodology used to build a culture of community resilience with the formation and strengthening of Community Risk Management Committees as agents of management, planning and first response. This work is qualitative, descriptive and ethnographic, because the problem is identified, putting it in evidence so that we were allowed to work in the empowerment of this subject within the community. We applied a questionnaire as an instrument to collect information about attitudes, knowledge and practices regarding risks due to tsunamis, as well as in-depth interviews on the subject with key actors. One of the conclusive results was that only 35\% of the population felt vulnerable by the tsunami threat, and 75\% do not feel prepared for a catastrophic event and the most dangerous is the 2\% of the population do not care. All these data has allowed us to take action and design an intervention strategy between the academy, government agencies and community.
