AB  - The Waikato Regional Council has a statutory responsibility to mitigate coastal flood hazards. The most significant issue is the pressure for development in flood prone areas, particularly those with some stopbank protection. This is compounded by a lack of quantitative data on the hazards. Problems experienced with traditional engineering approaches have led to a change in hazard management. A more comprehensive planning approach is now being used, facilitated by the Resource Management Act 1991 and subsidiary policy statements and plans. Further data gathering and analysis is required to identify the best management options. Extreme water levels, the true level of protection provided by stopbanks, and the amount of sea level rise to plan for must be determined. It is believed that this management strategy will help mitigate coastal flood hazards in the Waikato region. The effectiveness and efficiency of the various methods used will require monitoring.
