TY  - Article
TI  - Has Venice crossed the rubicon?
JO  - Geography
PY  - 2000
VL  - 85
IS  - 3
AB  - Flooding in Venice is an internationally renowned problem, and an icon for the threats that climate change and the associated sea-level rise might bring. This article chronicles the ideas that dominate the debate about providing flood protection for this important world heritage city. These include the famous proposal for mobile gates between the Lagoon and the sea and the counter arguments that stress the need for more sustainable solutions. Central to this analysis also is the complexity of political intrigue that surrounds everything in Venice, and the way that this discourse has fostered the constant shifting of opinions and decisions. Recent trends and `final' pronouncements suggest that the gates will never be built, but nothing is certain in Italy and re-crossing this Rubicon may indeed prove not to be sacrosanct.
