AB  - Climate-change problems in coastal zones are predominantly perceived from a water perspective. However, in accordance with the temporal and spatial scales at which the effects of climate change occur, we propose that coastal zones have to be regarded as sedimentary systems, rather than mere delimitations of a water system. Long-term coastal evolution is ultimately governed by the balance between demand and supplies of sediment so a sediment perspective on climate change and adaptation is an essential addition to the traditional water perspective. The coastal policy of the Netherlands is presented as an application of this perspective. We show that flood-risk in the coastal zone is, in essence, caused by sediment deficiency. The coast is managed accordingly, with coastal nourishments. We tentatively extend sediment-based adaptation options to the entire coastal plain, with examples such as a sustained land-raising effort or ultra-wide ('infallible') dikes. Based on preliminary estimates of sediment requirements and costs, such options seem feasible (technically and financially at least), and should be further explored
