AB  - The potential effects of climate change on large coastal cities have been addressed in scientific literature over the past 10-15 years. Climate change and sea level rise may exacerbate flood risks as well as river peak discharges. As a consequence, the vulnerability of infrastructure, people, nature and other economic sectors is increasing. Future climatic developments need to be taken into account in current urban and port development plans. It is important to reserve the space that will be required in the future for water storage, and to prepare projects that will be necessary to enhance protection against flooding and guarantee accessibility. In addition, design and construction concepts have to be adjusted both at the level of urban planning and at the individual building level. Taking these steps now will generate innovations that can also be marketed elsewhere in a later phase. This chapter discusses the water sensitive design initiatives that Rotterdam is taking, using climate change as a catalyst for urban design that is `climate proof' but also using water to improve the overall urban environment. The city of Rotterdam has decided to make the region `climate proof', in other words, to create a system that is sufficiently robust and that can adapt in good time to changes as they occur. Innovative applications in the area of water management will make the city more attractive. Examples include the construction of water plazas and floating structures.
