AB  - This paper has demonstrated through the examples of the Holderness, East Anglian and Essex coastline, the importance of changes in offshore bathymetry and hence rates of cliffline and coastal erosion and accretion. Along the Holderness coastline, comparisons of the historical map and charts have highlighted several distinct phases of offshore accretion and erosion between 1830 and 1984. Although it is difficult to argue that these changes are cyclical it is apparent that offshore changes are an important contributing factor to cliff erosion at Holderness. It has not been possible to relate wave energy to offshore changes and cliff erosion rates because of the lack of data, except for a short, very recent period. These observations lend further support for future studies of the offshore area, including a bathymetry survey especially as erosion affects coastal infrastructure and property. The distinct cyclical pattern of movement operating within the sandbanks offshore of Great Yarmouth has long temporal oscillations, e.g. 50-70 year, which affect navigation and the coastline. Although a cyclical pattern is not as apparent in the Thames Estuary, sandbank movement controls wave energy and hence potential coastal changes. Of the three areas investigated the offshore zone rarely reaches equilibrium and consequently neither does the coastline they partly protect. Although areas of stability exist, the identification of these long-term cyclical changes in the offshore zone is important for coastal defences and the development of appropriate shoreline management strategies.
